         b'e Work | <a href="assessment.php">Assessment</a>      <p/>\n\n<tab'
         b'le width="100%" cellpadding=6 cellspacing=1 bgcolor="#a0a0b0" >\n'
         b'<tr bgcolor="#e8e8f0">\n<th align=left><font size=\\"+2\\">Path Tra'
         b'cing assignment reading list</font></th>\n</tr>\n<tr bgcolor="#fff'
         b'fff"> <td> \n<p>\n\n<p align="justify">The following are pretty goo'
         b'd suggestions of what to read to get to grips writing a Monte-Carlo '
         b'path tracer. <a href="#[8]">[8]</a> has more in-depth material on ho'
         b'w to perform the direct lighting computations, and <a href="#[9]">[9'
         b']</a> is useful if you have a good idea of the overall algorithm but'
         b' need to look up specific formulas.</p>\n\n<p align="justify"><u>M'
         b'att Pharr\x92s</u> suggestions on reading to understand how to writ'
         b'e a path\ntracer (edited):</p>\n\n<p align="justify">I think that t'
         b'he best way to approach all this is starting with more recent papers'
         b'/notes, rather than the originals. With the passage of time comes mo'
         b're clarity/better ways of explaining things and it allows one to get'
         b' the right foundations down before going back to the papers where it'
         b' was all being first worked out.</p>\n\n<p align="justify">That sa'
         b"id, I'd strongly suggest that you start with the course notes from t"
         b'he Advanced Mote Carlo course from SIGGRAPH 2001 <a href="#[1]">[1]<'
         b"/a>. I'd also suggest that you work up to path tracing and bidirecti"
         b'onal path tracing by way of first focusing on the so-called direct l'
         b'ighting problem - computing reflected light at a point on a surface '
         b'with a complex BRDF due to illumination from an area light source - '
         b'as a way to build up intuition and experience.</p>\n\n<p align="ju'
         b'stify">That said, from those SIGGRAPH notes, the chapters by Peter S'
         b'hirley and Jim Arvo on the fundamentals of Monte Carlo integration a'
         b'nd techniques for sampling BRDFs and light sources are good to under'
         b'stand as well.</p>\n\n<p align="justify">Every hour you spent gett'
         b'ing a handle on the basics of Monte Carlo will pay off many times as'
         b' you go forward, since it will save you a lot of time adding and rem'
         b'oving factors of PI and cos(theta) from your implementation until yo'
         b'u stumble upon the right formulation.</p>\n\n<p align="justify">Pe'
         b"ter Shirley et al's paper on sampling area light source is also quit"
         b'e good and worth working through carefully <a href="#[5]">[5]</a>.</'
         b'p>\n\n<p align="justify">Having gone through that, read Arvo\'s wri'
         b'te-up of multiple importance sampling in the SIGGRAPH course notes a'
         b'nd Chapter 9 of Veach\'s PhD thesis <a href="#[6]">[6]</a>.</p>\n\n'
         b'<p align="justify">Make sure you understand how to apply multiple im'
         b'portance sampling to direct lighting and why it works well.</p>\n'
         b'\n<p align="justify">Then, onward to path tracing which is the sa'
         b"me thing as Monte Carlo path tracing. Check out Hanrahan's section i"
         b"n those SIGGRAPH course notes, and Veach's path integral formulation"
         b' of the rendering equation (in Chapter 8 of his thesis).</p>\n\n<p'
         b' align="justify">The rendering equation is often presented in a form'
         b' that tempts one to solve it recursively; the path integral way of t'
         b'hinking about what the rendering equation says is a lot more powerfu'
         b'l.</p>\n\n<p align="justify">Then go back and read Kajiya\'s paper '
         b'<a href="#[3]">[3]</a>, though keep in mind his terminology and form'
         b'ulation of the rendering equation are different than what is in use '
         b'today.</p>\n\n<p align="justify">If you understand the path integr'
         b'al way of thinking about the rendering equation, basic bidirectional'
         b' path tracing is a relatively small generalization. Read the corresp'
         b"onding chapter of Veach's thesis as well as Eric Lafortune's papers/"
         b'PhD thesis <a href="#[4]">[4]</a>.</p>\n\n<p align="justify">Henri'
         b'k Wann Jensen\'s papers on photon mapping <a href="#[2]">[2]</a> '
         b'are a good way to understand that technique; his recent book also co'
         b"vers the topic. You should also read\nGreg Ward's papers on irrad"
         b'iance caching <a href="#[7]">[7]</a>.</p>\n<br><br>\n<p align="jus'
         b'tify"><u>References</u></p>\n\n<p align="justify"><a name="[1]">[1'
         b']</a> James Arvo, Marcos Fajardo, Pat Hanrahan, Henrik W. Jensen, Do'
         b'n P. Mitchell, Matt Pharr, and Peter S. Shirley, \n<a href="mc-co'
         b'urse_notes__sig91.pdf">State of the Art in Monte\nCarlo Ray Traci'
         b'ng for Realistic Image Synthesis</a>, 2001.</p>\n\n<p align="justi'
         b'fy"><a name="[2]">[2]</a> Henrik W. Jensen, <a href="jensen__importa'
         b'nce_driven_path_tracing__1995.pdf">Importance Driven Path Tracing us'
         b'ing the Photon\nMap</a>, <i>Proc.6th Eurographics Workshop on Ren'
         b'dering</i>, 1995, pp. 326-335.</p>\n\n<p align="justify"><a name="'
         b'[3]">[3]</a> James T. Kajiya, <a href="Kajiya_J_T__The_Rendering_Equ'
         b'ation__SIGGRAPH86.pdf">The Rendering Equation</a>, <i>Computer\nG'
         b'raphics</i>, 20(4), 1986, pp. 143-150.</p>\n\n<p align="justify"><'
         b'a name="[4]">[4]</a> Eric P. F. Lafortune, <a href="LaFortune_E_P__M'
         b'athematical_Models_And_Monte_Carlo_Algorithms_For_Physically_Based_R'
         b'endering__PhDthesis.pdf">Mathematical Models and Monte Carlo\nAlg'
         b'orithms for Physically Based Rendering</a>, PhD thesis, Katholieke U'
         b'niversiteit Leuven, February 1996.</p>\n\n<p align="justify"><a na'
         b'me="[5]">[5]</a> Peter Shirley, Changyaw Wang, and Kurt Zimmerma'
         b'n, \n<a href="shirley__MC_techniques_for_direct_lighting__tog96.p'
         b'df">Monte Carlo Techniques for Direct Lighting Calculations</a>, <i>'
         b'ACM Transactions on Graphics</i>, 15(1), 1996, pp. 1-36.</p>\n\n<p'
         b' align="justify"><a name="[6]">[6]</a> Eric Veach, <a href="veach__t'
         b'hesis.pdf">Robust Monte Carlo Methods for Light Transport Simulation'
         b'</a>, PhD thesis, Stanford University, December 1997</p>\n\n<p ali'
         b'gn="justify"><a name="[7]">[7]</a> Gregory J. Ward and Paul S. Heckb'
         b'ert, <a href="Ward_G_J__Irradiance_Gradients__1992.pdf">Irradiance G'
         b'radients</a>, <i>Proc.3rd Eurographics Workshop on Rendering</i>, Ma'
         b'y 1992, pp. 85-98.</p>\n\n<p align="justify"><a name="[8]">[8]</a>'
         b' Changyaw Wang, <a href="wang__the_direct_lighting_computation_in_GI'
         b'__phd.pdf">The Direct Lighting Computation in Global Illumination</a'
         b'>, Indiana University, February 1994.</p>\n\n<p align="justify"><a'
